I considered this issue in the design of the current approach and I agree that a closer look is deserved; however, any performance degradation is likely to be traced back to #2546, which factored object equality from SimpleIRI to the shared AbstractIRI base class.
As far as I can see, the only relevant difference is in the timing of IRI.toString():
failing string object identity, both the original SimpleIRI.equals() and the updated AbstractIRI.equals() methods compare the return value of IRI.toString(), but:

in the case of SimpleIRI the value is precomputed in AbstractValueFactory as

public IRI createIRI(String namespace, String localName) {
	return createIRI(namespace + localName);
}

in the case of AbstractIRI the value is computed on demand on the basis of the public API as

public String stringValue() {
	return getNamespace() + getLocalName();
}
Back to you with some hard figures…
